A. Available benchmark instances:

1. Various benchmarks about flowshop scheduling problems (FSPs) can be downloaded from http://soa.iti.es/problem-instances, including the ones of permutation FSPs, no-wait FSPs, no-idle FSPs, mixed no-idle FSPs, hybrid FSPs, assembly FSPs, distributed permutation FSPs, and distributed assembly FSPs.
The instance are used in the following papers:
(1) Vallada, Eva, Ruiz, Rubén & Framinan, Jose M. (2017). New hard benchmark for flowshop scheduling problems minimising makespan. European Journal of Operational Research, 240, 666-677.
(2) Quan-Ke, Pan, Ruiz, Rubén & Alfaro-Fernández, Pedro. (2017). Iterated search methods for earliness and tardiness minimization in hybrid flowshops with due windows. Computers & Operations Research, 80, 50-60.M. Ciavotta, G. Minella and R. Ruiz, (2013). 
(3) Multi-objective sequence dependent setup times flowshop scheduling: a new algorithm and a comprehensive study. European Journal of Operational Research, 227(2), 301-313
(4) Naderi, B. & Ruiz, Rubén, (2010). The distributed permutation flowshop scheduling problem. Computers & Operations Research, 37(4), 754-768.
(5) Naderi, B. & Ruiz, Rubén, (2014). A scatter search algorithm for the distributed permutation flowshop scheduling problem. European Journal of Operational Research, 239(2), 323-334.
(6) Ruiz, Rubén, Pan, Q.-K. & Naderi, B. (2018). Iterated Greedy methods for the distributed permutation flowshop scheduling problem. OMEGA, The International Journal of Management Science. In press.
(7) B. Naderi, R. Ruiz and M. Zandieh. (2008), Algorithms for a realistic variant of flowshop scheduling,  Computers & Operations Research, 37(2), 236-246.
(8) R. Ruiz, E. Vallada and Fernández-Martínez, C. (2009). Scheduling in flowshops with no-idle machines. Scheduling in flowshops with no-idle machines, chapter 2, pages 21-52 of the book "Computational Intelligence in Flow Shop and Job Shop Scheduling" edited by Uday K. Chakraborty. New York : Springer.
(9) R. Ruiz and A. Allahverdi, (2009). New heuristics for no-wait flowshops with bicriteria of makespan and maximum lateness. International Journal of Production Research, 47(20), 5717-5738.
(10) R. Ruiz, F. Sivrikaya Şerifoğlu and T. Urlings, (2008). Modeling realistic hybrid flexible flowshop scheduling problems. Computers & Operations Research 35, 1151-1175.
(11) T. Urlings, R. Ruiz and T. Stützle, (2010), Shifting representation search for hybrid flexible flowline problems, European Journal of Operational Research 207, 1086-1095.
(12) T. Urlings, R. Ruiz and F. Sivrikaya Şerifoğlu, (2010), Genetic algorithms with different representation schemes for complex hybrid flexible flow line problems, International Journal of Metaheuristics 1, 30-54.
(13) G. Minella, R. Ruiz and M. Ciavotta (2008). A Review and Evaluation of Multi-Objective Algorithms for the Flowshop Scheduling Problem. INFORMS Journal on Computing, 20(3): 451-471.
(14) G. Minella, R. Ruiz and M. Ciavotta (2011). Restarted Iterated Pareto Greedy algorithm for Multi-Objective Flowshop Scheduling problems.Computers & Operations Research, 38(11), 1521-1533.
(15) R. Ruiz and T. Stützle, (2008) An Iterated Greedy heuristic for the sequence dependent setup times flowshop with makespan and weighted tardiness objectives. European Journal of Operational Research 187, 1143-1159.
(16) E. Vallada, R. Ruiz and G. Minella, (2008). Minimizing total tardiness in the m-machine flowshop problem: a review and evaluation of heuristics and metaheuristics. Computers & Operations Research 35, 1350-1373.
(17) E. Vallada and R. Ruiz, (2009). Cooperative Metaheuristics for the Permutation Flowshop Scheduling Problem.  European Journal of Operational Research, 193(2): 365-376.
(18) E. Vallada and R. Ruiz, (2010).Genetic algorithms with path relinking for the minimum tardiness permutation flowshop problem. OMEGA, The International Journal of Management Science, 38(1-2), 57-67.
(19) R. Ruiz and A. Allahverdi, (2007). No-Wait Flowshop with Separate Setup Times to Minimize Maximum Lateness. International Journal of Advanced Manufacturing Technology 35, 551-565.
(20) R. Ruiz and A. Allahverdi, (2007). Some Effective Heuristics for No-Wait Flowshops with Setup Times to Minimize Total Completion Time. Annals of Operations Research 156, 143-171.
(21) R. Ruiz, J. Carlos García-Díaz and C. Maroto, (2007). Considering scheduling and preventive maintenance in the flowshop sequencing problem. Computers & Operations Research 34, 3314-3330.
(22) R. Ruiz, C. Maroto and J. Alcaraz (2005). Solving the flowshop scheduling problem with sequence dependent setup times using advanced metaheuristics. European Journal of Operational Research 165, 34-54.
(23) R. Ruiz and T. Stützle, (2008) An Iterated Greedy heuristic for the sequence dependent setup times flowshop with makespan and weighted tardiness objectives. European Journal of Operational Research 187, 1143-1159.

2. A well-known Taillard’s benchmark of FSPs introduced in (1) is available at http://mistic.heig-vd.ch/taillard/problemes.dir/ordonnancement.dir/ordonnancement.html and used in the following papers.
(1) Taillard, Eric. "Benchmarks for basic scheduling problems." european journal of operational research 64.2 (1993): 278-285.
(2) Ding, Jian-Ya, et al. "New block properties for flowshop scheduling with blocking and their application in an iterated greedy algorithm." International Journal of Production Research 54.16 (2016): 4759-4772.
(3) Pan, Quan-Ke, Mehmet Fatih Tasgetiren, and Yun-Chia Liang. "A discrete differential evolution algorithm for the permutation flowshop scheduling problem." Computers & Industrial Engineering 55.4 (2008): 795-816.
(4) Zhuang, Wei Jin, Tao Xu, and Ming Yang Sun. "A hybrid iterated greedy algorithm for no-wait flowshop with sequence dependent setup times to minimize makespan." Advanced Materials Research. Vol. 933. Trans Tech Publications Ltd, 2014.
(5) Zhang, Chaoyong, et al. "An effective VNSSA algorithm for the blocking flowshop scheduling problem with makespan minimization." 2015 International Conference on Advanced Mechatronic Systems (ICAMechS). IEEE, 2015.
(6) Ravetti, Martín Gómez, et al. "Parallel hybrid heuristics for the permutation flow shop problem." Annals of Operations Research 199.1 (2012): 269-284.
(7) Balázs, Krisztián, Zoltán Horváth, and László T. Kóczy. "Multi-threaded bacterial Iterated Greedy heuristics for the Permutation Flow Shop Problem." 2012 IEEE 13th International Symposium on Computational Intelligence and Informatics (CINTI). IEEE, 2012.

3. Two datasets of FSPs are available at OR-library http://people.brunel.ac.uk/~mastjjb/jeb/orlib/flowshopinfo.html. 
 
4. A benchmark dataset of hybrid FSPs is available at www.benchmark.ibu.edu.tr/mpt-hfsp.
Şerifoğlu, F. Sivrikaya, and Gündüz Ulusoy. "Multiprocessor task scheduling in multistage hybrid flow-shops: a genetic algorithm approach." Journal of the Operational Research Society 55.5 (2004): 504-512.

B. Instance generation method:

1. Hybid FSPs:
Oğuz, Ceyda, et al. "Hybrid flow-shop scheduling problems with multiprocessor task systems." European Journal of Operational Research 152.1 (2004): 115-131.

2. Flexible FSPs:
Naderi, Bahman, Mostafa Zandieh, and GHOMI SEYED MOHAMMAD TAGHI FATEMI. "An Iterated Greedy Algorithm for Flexible Flow Lines with Sequence Dependent Setup Times to Minimize Total Weighted Completion Time." (2009): 33-37.

3. No-wait FSPs:
Ruiz, Ruben, and Ali Allahverdi. "New heuristics for no-wait flow shops with a linear combination of makespan and maximum lateness." International Journal of Production Research 47.20 (2009): 5717-5738.
